The ministry of education is considering suspending learning in universities and colleges for two weeks during the election period, guaranteeing student safety and time for them to vote on August 8.Education CS Fred Matiang&rsquo;i said yesterday he&rsquo;s in consultations with public university vice chancellors and college principals to suspend learning from August 4.&ldquo;This will allow learners in our institutions to go and vote and be with their parents. You will also have time to participate because I know that we contribute the highest number of election officials as an education sector,&rdquo; Matiang&rsquo;i said.He spoke during a meeting with administrators of educational and learning institutions at the KICD.Matiang&rsquo;i also said he has spoken IEBC chairman Wafula Chebukati to furnish the ministry with the number of institutions they will need on voting day for accountability purposes.&ldquo;It will not be a case where we walk out and the IEBC says we are coming here to loan two or three schools. We must know from IEBC which classrooms and facilities they need. The same with universities and colleges.&rdquo;Matiang&rsquo;i said he has also notified the electoral body that it will have to foot expenses for any damages that may occur at learning institutions during voting.&ldquo;We do not build schools so that they are destroyed. We are borrowing these facilities from our children; we must return them in good condition,&rdquo; he said.The CS further said political rallies or any other campaign activities within school premises are banned.Meanwhile, Matiang&rsquo;i called on VCs and college administrators to ensure that student safety is guaranteed during the campaign period.